      <hedline>
        <hl1>Help Rape Victims, Without Delay</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sara R Sills letter on report finding that more than half of emergency rooms in New York hospitals have failed to fofer rape victims emergency contraception, which can prevent pregnancy 95 percent of time if taken within 24 hours (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Sex Crimes, Evidence Depends on Game of Chance in Hospitals'' (front page, Aug. 6):</p>
        <p>A study conducted last summer by the National Abortion Rights Action League of New York State concluded that more than half of the emergency rooms in the state's hospitals failed to offer emergency contraception to rape survivors. Emergency contraception, if taken within 24 hours, can prevent pregnancy 95 percent of the time.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Sex Crimes, Evidence Depends on Game of Chance in Hospitals'' (front page, Aug. 6):</p>
        <p>A study conducted last summer by the National Abortion Rights Action League of New York State concluded that more than half of the emergency rooms in the state's hospitals failed to offer emergency contraception to rape survivors. Emergency contraception, if taken within 24 hours, can prevent pregnancy 95 percent of the time.</p>
        <p>Legislation addressing this omission was introduced in both state legislative bodies during the 1999-2000 session in Albany but failed to reach the floor of either house.</p>
        <p>This basic, compassionate medical service needs to be offered to rape survivors without delay in every emergency room. These women have already been victimized because of their gender; New York State should not allow their further victimization.</p>
        <p>SARA R. SILLS  Brooklyn, Aug. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
